\title{Trans-Triad: Transclusion Forest}
\taxon{forest}
\author{monaduck1069}
\date{2026-04-04}
\tag{transclusion}
\tag{transduction}
\tag{transitivity}
\meta{trit-sum}{0}

\import{macros}

\p{The skill forest has 1393 trees. 242 are connected by transclusion edges. 1097 are orphans — 82\% of total bytes. Five hub trees absorb 68\% of all inbound references. This tree maps the transclusion forest and marks the slop trail.}

\subtree{
\title{The Three Trans- Operations}

\subtree{
\title{Transclusion (−1, MINUS)}
\p{A skill declares what it \em{reads}, not what it \em{contains}. At load time the agent reads each source file, extracts matching content, injects as XML inside the Anthropic API's \code{\startverb <loaded_skill>\stopverb} tag.}

\p{The stub is the skill. The code is the content.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Transduction (0, ERGODIC)}
\p{Content passes \em{through} the skill and is transformed. 500 lines of server.rs becomes 15 lines of tool signatures. The skill is a lens, not a document.}

\p{Operations: extract, reshape, filter, annotate, compose.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Transitivity (+1, PLUS)}
\p{If skill A transclude from source B, and skill B transduces output C, then loading A produces C. Loading \code{\startverb beeper\stopverb} transitively gives you \code{\startverb signal-mcp\stopverb} tool signatures without loading \code{\startverb signal-messaging\stopverb} separately.}

\p{Transitivity makes the graph sparse. Each skill is a pointer. Content lives once, at the source.}
}
}

\transclude{bcf-0039}
